### Q: why would you delete this folder? dont do it but just for sake of question?
Q: sudo rm -rf /var/lib/elasticsearch/*
ðŸ“ What is /var/lib/ in Linux?
/var/lib/ is a standard directory in Linux used to store persistent application data â€” the kind that changes as programs run.

It's like the "workspace" for services that need to keep track of state, databases, user sessions, etc.

ðŸ“¦ So what's /var/lib/elasticsearch/?
For Elasticsearch, this directory stores the entire node's data, including:

Subdirectory / File	What's in it
nodes/	Node ID, cluster state, shard data
indices/	All the actual index data (your documents, mappings, etc.)
translog/	Transaction logs (used for recovery in case of crash)
state-*.st	Metadata about cluster state, node state
Think of it as Elasticsearchâ€™s memory, database, and journal all rolled into one.

ðŸ”„ Why is it important?
Elasticsearch wonâ€™t work without this directory.

If it's corrupted or doesnâ€™t match your config (like different node name or discovery setup), Elasticsearch might fail to start or try to connect to ghost nodes (like what you're seeing).

If you delete it, you wipe all data, and Elasticsearch will create a new clean state.

âœ… Summary
Directory	Purpose
/var/lib/elasticsearch/	Where Elasticsearch stores all of its persistent data â€” indices, cluster state, etc.
Should I delete it?	Only if youâ€™re okay losing all data and starting fresh (e.g., during dev or reset)
Can I move or back it up?	Yes â€” you can archive it or point path.data to another location in elasticsearch.yml


